The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Hyundai, Skoda slash prices

 New Delhi, March 3 (PTI): Skoda Auto India, a fully owned subsidiary of Czech company Skoda Auto, today announced price cuts up to Rs 50,000 on its various car models following the reduction in peak rate customs duty to 15 per cent in the Union budget.

 The price changes would come into effect from today, a company release said.

 ?Having analysed the fine print of the budget, the company has decided to pass on as benefit to the customers of up to Rs 50,000,? Skoda Auto managing director Imran Hassen said.

 Skoda Auto sells Octavia and Superb models in India. In February, the company sold 306 units, of which 15 were Skoda Superb.

 Skoda Auto has been operating in the country since 2001 as a subsidiary of Volkswagen group company Skoda Auto. It has manufacturing facility in Shendra near Aurangabad in Maharashtra.

 The company now has eight luxury models in the country ? the top end Skoda L amp;K, Skoda Elegance, Skoda Automatic, Skoda Ambient E, Skoda Rider, Skoda RS, Skoda Superb and Skoda Rider 1.8 turbo.

 Sonata to cost less

 Hyundai Motor India Ltd reported a 17.84 per cent dip in its domestic car sales for February, and said it would soon reduce the price of its high import intensity models, Elantra and Sonata.

 HMIL president B. V. R. Subbu said the company is considering revising the prices of Elantra and Sonata downwards in the wake of the customs duty cut. 




